The app doesn't use `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()`, so it can't handle POST/PUT requests yet. When you add them, **always set size limits** to prevent denial-of-service via large payloads.

```js
// ❌ Dangerous (no limit — default is 100kb, but be explicit)
app.use(express.json());

// ✅ Secure
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

### 2. No Helmet (Missing Security Headers) — OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration

Express sends no security headers by default. This leaves the app vulnerable to clickjacking, MIME sniffing, and XSS.

```js
// ✅ Add helmet
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

This sets `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, and more.

### 3. No Rate Limiting — OWASP A04: Insecure Design

Both endpoints are unprotected against brute-force or DoS attacks.

```js
// ✅ Add rate limiting
